[30;1m5 | [0m[35mis called when no other suitable method/object could be found.[0m
[30;1m6 | [0m[35mEssentially, if CherryPy2 can't find a matching request handler object[0m
[30;1m7 | [0m[35mfor the given request URI, it will use the default method of the object[0m
[30;1m8 | [0m[35mlocated deepest on the URI path.[0m
[30;1m9 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m19 | [0m[35m#[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35m# Autoreload examines sys.modules afresh every time it runs. If an application[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35m# changes the current directory by executing os.chdir(), then the next time[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35m# Autoreload runs, it will not be able to find any filenames which are[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35m# not absolute paths, because the current directory is not the same as when the[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35m# module was first imported.  Autoreload will then wrongly conclude the file[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35m# has "changed", and initiate the shutdown/re-exec sequence.[0m

[30;1m32 | [0m[35mCherryPy *Requests* are part of an *Application*, which runs in a *global*[0m

[30;1m25 | [0m[35mThe first thing you need to know about CherryPy 3's configuration is that it[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35mseparates *global* config from *application* config. If you're deploying[0m
[30;1m27 | [0m[35mmultiple *applications* at the same *site* (and more and more people are,[0m
[30;1m28 | [0m[35mas Python web apps are tending to decentralize), you need to be careful to[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35mseparate the configurations, as well. There's only ever one "global config",[0m
[30;1m30 | [0m[35mbut there is a separate "app config" for each app you deploy.[0m

[30;1m166 | [0m[35m~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~[0m

[30;1m168 | [0m[35mIn order to support its life-cycle, CherryPy defines a set[0m
[30;1m169 | [0m[35mof common channels that will be published to at various states:[0m
[30;1m170 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m171 | [0m[35m- **"start"**: When the bus is in the `"STARTING"` state[0m
[30;1m172 | [0m[35m- **"main"**: Periodically from the CherryPy's mainloop[0m

[30;1m137 | [0m[35m~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~[0m
[30;1m138 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m139 | [0m[35mAs said earlier, CherryPy is built around a pubsub bus. All[0m
[30;1m140 | [0m[35mentities that the framework manages at runtime are working on[0m
[30;1m141 | [0m[35mtop of a single bus instance, which is named the `engine`.[0m

[30;1m279 | [0m[35mWhen you stream, your application doesn't immediately pass raw body content[0m
[30;1m280 | [0m[35mback to CherryPy or to the HTTP server. Instead, it passes back a generator.[0m
[30;1m281 | [0m[35mAt that point, CherryPy finalizes the status and headers, **before** the[0m
[30;1m282 | [0m[35mgenerator has been consumed, or has produced any output. This is necessary to[0m
[30;1m283 | [0m[35mallow the HTTP server to send the headers and pieces of the body as they become[0m
[30;1m284 | [0m[35mavailable.[0m

[30;1m244 | [0m[35m###########################[0m
[30;1m245 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m246 | [0m[35mCherryPy handles HTTP requests, packing and unpacking the low-level details,[0m
[30;1m247 | [0m[35mthen passing control to your application's :term:`page handler`, which produce[0m
[30;1m248 | [0m[35mthe body of the response. CherryPy allows you to return body content in a[0m
[30;1m249 | [0m[35mvariety of types: a string, a list of strings, a file. CherryPy also allows you[0m
[30;1m250 | [0m[35mto *yield* content, rather than *return* content. When you use "yield", you also[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m699[0m[34m of [0m[33m1005[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Windows[0m
